    id: 21,
    level: 'intermediate',
    topic: 'Finance',
    title: 'Understanding Credit and Debt',
    passage: `In today's world, understanding how credit and debt work is one of the most important life skills a person can have. Whether you are buying a phone on instalments, taking out a loan for education, or simply using a credit card to pay for groceries, you are participating in a system that can either work powerfully in your favour or quietly destroy your financial wellbeing — depending on how well you understand it.

Credit, at its most basic level, is borrowed money. When a bank or financial institution gives you credit, they are trusting you to repay the money you borrow, usually with interest added on top. Interest is the cost of borrowing — it is the extra money you pay the lender in exchange for using their money. Interest is usually expressed as an annual percentage rate, or APR. For example, if you borrow one thousand dollars at an APR of 20 percent, you will owe an extra two hundred dollars per year if you do not repay the principal — the original amount borrowed.

Credit cards are one of the most common forms of credit in modern life. They allow you to buy things now and pay for them later. Most credit cards give you a grace period — typically around thirty days — during which you can repay the full balance without paying any interest. However, if you only pay the minimum payment — the smallest amount the credit card company requires you to pay each month — the remaining balance carries over to the next month and begins accumulating interest. This is how many people fall into what financial experts call the "debt trap." You borrow a small amount, pay only the minimum each month, and the interest compounds — meaning it grows on top of itself — until you owe far more than you originally borrowed.

Debt is not always a negative thing. Economists distinguish between "good debt" and "bad debt." Good debt is money borrowed to invest in something that will increase in value or generate income over time — such as a mortgage to buy a home or a student loan to fund an education that leads to higher earning potential. Bad debt, on the other hand, is money borrowed to pay for things that lose value quickly or provide no financial return — such as borrowing money to buy luxury goods, take an expensive holiday, or cover everyday expenses you cannot otherwise afford.

One of the most powerful concepts in personal finance is the idea of living within your means. This simply means not spending more than you earn. People who consistently spend more than they earn inevitably accumulate debt, which becomes increasingly difficult to pay off over time due to the power of compound interest working against them. In contrast, people who spend less than they earn have money left over to save and invest, allowing compound interest to work in their favour.

Managing debt effectively requires a clear strategy. Financial advisers often recommend two main approaches. The first is called the "avalanche method" — you list all your debts and focus on paying off the one with the highest interest rate first, while making minimum payments on all others. Once the highest-interest debt is paid off, you move to the next highest. This approach saves the most money in interest over time. The second approach is the "snowball method" — you focus on paying off the smallest debt first, regardless of interest rate, to build momentum and psychological motivation. Once the smallest debt is gone, you roll that payment into the next smallest, and so on.

Understanding the difference between a want and a need is also central to healthy financial habits. A need is something essential for survival and basic functioning — food, shelter, healthcare, transportation to work. A want is something desirable but not essential — a new phone when your old one still works, eating at a restaurant instead of cooking at home, or upgrading to a larger apartment when your current one is adequate. Blurring the line between wants and needs is one of the primary reasons people accumulate unnecessary debt.

Ultimately, the relationship you have with money and debt is deeply personal and often influenced by the financial habits you observed growing up. However, regardless of your starting point, the principles of financial literacy — understanding interest, avoiding unnecessary debt, living within your means, and saving consistently — can be learned and applied at any stage of life.`,
